Introduction to the data set

The data we use in this project comes from two datasets on Portuguese students and their performance in math (395 observations) and Portuguese (649 observations) courses. 382 students belong to both datasets and while we mainly work with the datasets separately, some of our analysis involves the joint dataset. There are 33 predictors in both datasets involving information such as school, sex, age, information about the students study and lifestyle habits, family details, and three grades. We acknowledge that the earlier grades (G1, G2) are helpful in predicting the final grade (G3) and we explore models with and without G1 and G2. The full list and description of predictors can be found at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance.

We first perform Exploratory Data Analysis to understand relationships between predictors and grades, involving interesting trends between grades and school, parents jobs, alcohol consumption, health, and family relationships.

Then we move into building a linear model to predict G3 to get an idea of what kind of results we can obtain from a basic model.

We then attempt to explore and answer various questions including: What are the most important variables in predicting a students grade? Which variables have a similar effect in predicting grades? What attributes are common among similarly performing students? What attributes are most helpful in predicting the school a student attends? What attributes are most helpful in predicting internet access?

To investigate these questions, we used a variety of prediction methods and models including clustering, random forests, lasso, subset selection, and PCA.

d1=read.table("~/Downloads/student/student-mat.csv",sep=";",header=TRUE)

Other trends that we found that are not surprising:

  • students with the highest travel time have lower average grades in both math and Portuguese.

  • higher grades are attributed to more study time, less previous failures, and intent to pursue higher education.

  • students receiving extra academic support have lower average grades.

Predicting student grades

Linear model

Run a model to predict each math and Portuguese students grade individually and then look at if the model holds up when predicting students who took both. We also create a train and test combo for both data sets.

mattrain <- sample(1:nrow(d1), (nrow(d1)/2))
portrain <- sample(1:nrow(d2), (nrow(d2)/2))
train.mat = d1[mattrain,]
train.mat = subset(train.mat, select = -c(G1,G2))
train.por = d1[portrain,]
train.por = subset(train.por, select = -c(G1,G2))

test.mat = d1[-mattrain,]
test.mat = subset(test.mat, select = -c(G1,G2))
test.por = d1[-portrain,]
test.por = subset(test.por, select = -c(G1,G2))

Here are the actual models!

mod_math <- lm(scale(G3) ~ . , data=train.mat)
mod_por <- lm(scale(G3) ~ . , data=train.por)

How well do they predict on their own test sets? How well do they predict for each others test sets?

test.mat.preds <- predict(mod_math, data=test.mat)
test.por.preds <- predict(mod_por, data=test.por)

SVM

We created a variable called performance that creates three categories of performance: 1- high, 2-average, 3-low. Then we run the SVM algorithm to classify students based on the other available predictors. We found slightly better results using a polynomial and radial kernel, so we stuck with radial kernel.

theCost <- 10

data.df <- d3[,c("school","sex","age","address","famsize","Pstatus","Medu","Fedu",
                 "Mjob","Fjob","reason","nursery","internet","G3.x","G3.y")]

data.df$mathperformance <- factor(ifelse(data.df$G3.x > 16, 1, 
            ifelse(data.df$G3.x > mean(data.df$G3.x) & data.df$G3.x <= 16, 2, 3)))

data.df$porperformance <- factor(ifelse(data.df$G3.y > 16, 1, 
            ifelse(data.df$G3.y > mean(data.df$G3.y) & data.df$G3.y <= 16, 2, 3)))

data.df$id <- 1:nrow(data.df)

test.sample <- sample(1:nrow(data.df), (nrow(data.df)/2))
test.df <- data.df[test.sample,]
data.df <- data.df[-test.sample,]

# Math model
mod.svm.math <- svm(mathperformance~.,
               data=subset(data.df, 
               select=-c(id, porperformance, G3.x, G3.y)),
               kernel="radial",
               cost=theCost,
               scale=F)

# Portuguese model
mod.svm.por <- svm(porperformance~.,
               data=subset(data.df, 
               select=-c(id, mathperformance, G3.x, G3.y)),
               kernel="radial",
               cost=theCost,
               scale=F)

test.df$predmath <- predict(mod.svm.math, 
            data=subset(test.df, select=-c(id, porperformance, G3.x, G3.y)))
test.df$predpor <- predict(mod.svm.por, 
            data=subset(test.df, select=-c(id, mathperformance, G3.x, G3.y, predmath)))

math_perf_accuracy <- round(1-mean(test.df$mathperformance != test.df$predmath), digits=2)

por_perf_accuracy <- round(1-mean(test.df$porperformance != test.df$predpor), digits=2)

The prediction accuracy for math performance is 0.46 and the prediction accuracy for Portuguese performance is 0.43. Since we have three categories, the accuracy is better than a coinflip, but not high at all. Though it seems better than the MSE in our linear model, which was in the hundreds for a quantitative variable with 20 as its maximum value.

Clustering

To get a better understanding of the relationships between the predictors, we will perform unsupervised learning on the common variables across the two data sets using the hierarchical clustering algorithm and cutting the resulting tree at a reasonable height to obtain clusters.

Here we will be working with the combined data set, which consists of students who are in the math class as well as the Portuguese class.

Heres the hierarchical cluster:

hierclust <- hclust(student_dists)
plot(hierclust)

Now we perform the cut to obtain the clusters.

cuttr <- cutree(hierclust, h=0.1)
simvars <- as.data.frame(cuttr)
colnames(simvars) <- "Cluster"
simvars$Variable <- names(cuttr)
simvars%>% ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(Cluster, Variable))

Mothers education and fathers job, along with sex of the student, seems to differentiate the students performance the most. Its interesting to see some of the natural clusters of predictors that appear in this plot (things about the father, things about the mother). For math, we see that hierarchical clustering shows that the predictors age, access to nursery, and access to internet are clustered together. For Portuguese, we see that the occupation of the father and the male children are clustered together. How do these natural clusters compare with things from PCA?

Variable analysis

PCA

We will use PCA to visualize how the variables in both the math and Portuguese data sets relate to one another.

mathStudents <- d1
portStudents <- d2
# convert predictors to numeric
for(i in colnames(mathStudents)){
    mathStudents[,i] <- as.numeric(mathStudents[,i])
    portStudents[,i] <- as.numeric(portStudents[,i])
}
# scale
d1_pca <- data.frame(scale(mathStudents))
d2_pca <- data.frame(scale(portStudents))
# initial clustering
K <- 5
mathMod.km <- kmeans(d1_pca,K,nstart=25) 
portMod.km <- kmeans(d2_pca,K,nstart=25) 
# fviz_cluster - compute the principal components for math
mathMod.pc <- prcomp(d1_pca)
fviz_pca_var(mathMod.pc) + 
  ggtitle("PCA for Math students")

# fviz_cluster - compute the principal components for Portuguese
portMod.pc <- prcomp(d2_pca)
fviz_pca_var(portMod.pc) + 
  ggtitle("PCA for Portuguese students")

The trends and grouping of the predictors are similar across math and Portuguese. In one grouping we see travel time, failures, age, and school, guardian, and romantic. We saw earlier that GP is a higher performing school and there are less young students at MS. In EDA, we also observed that long travel time is correlated with lower grades, which could tie into number of failures. Note, however, that these clusters of predictors appear to differ from the clusters we found in the hierarchical clustering.

Another grouping includes Walc, Dalc, freetime, goout, health, absences. These all seem naturally related to each other. Students with more free time may be prone to go out and consume alcohol, which may impact their health and attendance.

The last larger grouping includes Medu, Fedu, Mjob, Fjob, higher, studytime, address, internet, reason, famrel, famsup, paid, and nursery. This grouping makes sense as parents education influences their careers, as well as their childs study habits and education goals.

Lasso

Well use lasso to build a model and identify the predictors that correspond to an optimal lambda value. Well compare these important predictors to the groupings we found in PCA and compare the MSE to our linear model.

# select only numeric predictors since lasso is not compatible with factors
d1_lasso <- select_if(d1, is.numeric)
d2_lasso <- select_if(d2, is.numeric)

# build test and train data sets for math students
mysample <- sample(1:nrow(d1_lasso), nrow(d1_lasso)/2)
d1train.df <- drop_na(d1_lasso[mysample,])
d1test.df <- drop_na(d1_lasso[-mysample,])
x.d1train <- as.matrix(d1train.df[,-c(14,15,16)])
x.d1test <- as.matrix(d1test.df[,-c(14,15,16)])
y.d1train <- d1train.df[,16] 
y.d1test <- d1test.df[,16]

# build test and train data sets for Portuguese students
mysample <- sample(1:nrow(d2_lasso), nrow(d2_lasso)/2)
d2train.df <- drop_na(d2_lasso[mysample,])
d2test.df <- drop_na(d2_lasso[-mysample,])
x.d2train <- as.matrix(d2train.df[,-c(14,15,16)])
x.d2test <- as.matrix(d2test.df[,-c(14,15,16)])
y.d2train <- d2train.df[,16] 
y.d2test <- d2test.df[,16]

Build a grid of lambda values

Subset selection

Well use subset selection to find a subset of predictors which reduce MSE the most. Well compare this set of predictors to the groupings found in PCA and lasso.

d1_subset <- d1 # math
d2_subset <- d2 # Portuguese
for(i in ncol(d1_subset)){
  d1_subset[,i] <- as.numeric(d1_subset[,i])
  d2_subset[,i] <- as.numeric(d2_subset[,i])
}
d1_subset <- d1_subset[-c(31,32)] # remove g1 and g2
d2_subset <- d2_subset[-c(31,32)] # remove g1 and g2
numRows <- nrow(d1_subset)
train <- sample(1:numRows,numRows/2,rep=F)
# math
train1.df <- d1_subset[train,]
test1.df <- d1_subset[-train,]

# Portuguese
train2.df <- d2_subset[train,]
test2.df <- d2_subset[-train,]

Function for computing CV mse.

mseCV <- function(data.df,kfolds=10){
  sampleSize <- nrow(data.df)
  folds <- sample(1:kfolds,sampleSize,rep=T)
  mse <- rep(0,kfolds)
  for(k in 1:kfolds){
    train.df <- data.df[folds !=k,]
    test.df <- data.df[folds==k,]
    mod <- lm(G3~.,data=train.df)
    vals <- predict(mod,newdata=test.df)
    mse[k] <- with(test.df,mean((G3-vals)^2))
  }
  mean(mse)
}

Compare mses of math and Portuguese with CV.

# Math
mseCV(d1_subset)
## [1] 18.95604
# Portuguese
mseCV(d2_subset)
## [1] 7.413482

Again we see a trend that the mse for predicting Portuguese grades is lower than math.

Now we will use a loop to continually add the predictor with the smallest mse in hopes of finding a subset of predictors that gives us the optimal mse. First, we will run the process for the math dataset.

numPreds <- length(names(d1_subset))-1
allPreds <- 1:(numPreds)
currPreds <- c()
availPreds <- setdiff(allPreds,currPreds) # takes out currPreds from allPreds
maxPreds <- numPreds
minMSE <- numeric(maxPreds)

tot <- 0
while( tot < maxPreds){
  # add predictor which decreases MSE
  # The MSEs computed as we add each of the available predictors
  allMSE <- numeric(length(availPreds))
  ctr<-1
  for(id in availPreds){
    data.df <- d1_subset[,c(currPreds,id,numPreds+1)]
    mse <- mseCV(data.df,5)
    allMSE[ctr] <- mse
    ctr<-ctr+1
  }
  # Find the min mse
  id <- which.min(allMSE)
  # get the best predictor and MSE
  bestPred <- availPreds[id]
  bestMSE <- min(allMSE)
  # Add these into the collection
  currPreds <- c(currPreds,bestPred)
  tot <-tot+1
  minMSE[tot] <- bestMSE
  availPreds <- setdiff(allPreds,currPreds)
  #print(sprintf("Predictor Added: %s  MSE Value: %s",bestPred,bestMSE))
  #print(currPreds)
}
data.frame(pred=1:maxPreds,minMSE) %>% 
  ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(pred,minMSE)) +
  ggtitle("Number of predictors vs MSE for math")

Which predictors are in the subset with the lowest MSE for math?

bestPreds <- currPreds[1:which.min(minMSE)]
(bestPredNames <- names(d1_subset)[currPreds[1:which.min(minMSE)]])
##  [1] "failures"   "Medu"       "famsup"     "Mjob"       "age"       
##  [6] "traveltime" "paid"       "romantic"   "famsize"    "schoolsup" 
## [11] "Dalc"       "sex"

We see a few of the same predictors from lasso show up in this subset of predictors. Mothers education is important in predicting grades in math, but the most important predictor is failures, which also had the strongest negative correlation with grades in the lasso model and PCA.

Random Forests and Variable Importance

How does a random forest predict whether a student passes their course? For this analysis, we suppose that any grade above a 10 is passing, and below is failing. We then look at the variable importance plots to see what attributes are most important for the random forest.

# create dataframes, clean
d1.bin = d1
d1.bin$pass = factor(ifelse(d1$G3 >= 10, "yes", "no"))
d2.bin = d2
d2.bin$pass = factor(ifelse(d2$G3 >= 10, "yes", "no"))
d1.bin = subset(d1.bin, select = -c(G1,G2,G3))
d2.bin = subset(d2.bin, select = -c(G1,G2,G3))

# make the models!
p <- ncol(d1.bin)
mod.bag.d1 <- randomForest(pass~.,
                         data=d1.bin,
                         mtry=p, ##use all the predictors
                         ntree=100) ## 100 trees

mod.bag.d2 <- randomForest(pass~.,
                         data=d2.bin,
                         mtry=p, ##use all the predictors
                         ntree=100) ## 100 trees

Lets take a look at what was important for the math students.

temp1 = data.frame(importance(mod.bag.d1)) 
ggplot(data = temp1, aes(x=reorder(row.names(temp1), -MeanDecreaseGini), 
                         y=MeanDecreaseGini, fill=MeanDecreaseGini)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge",stat="identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title="Predicting passing grade\nVariable importance for Math students", x="Variables")

Absences and failures are very important in predicting whether a student passes or not. That makes a lot of sense! Lets look at what happens with the Portuguese data set.

temp2 = data.frame(importance(mod.bag.d2)) 
ggplot(data = temp2, aes(x=reorder(row.names(temp2), -MeanDecreaseGini), 
                         y=MeanDecreaseGini, fill=MeanDecreaseGini)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge",stat="identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title="Predicting passing grade\nVariable importance for Portuguese students", x="Variables")

Again, absences and failures account for a lot of the random forests decisions. Its interesting to note that this random forest model agrees with what we saw in PCA, that failures and final grades were in opposite directions on the same dimension.

We are also interested in predicting things about students other than their grades like which school they attended, their gender, or whether or not they plan to go into higher education. We attempted to create models using random forests to answer these questions on both data sets. Much like our difficulties with k-means clustering, we did not have too much success in prediction. This was partially due to how certain attributes we nearly all the same among students (i.e.nearly all students didnt have supplemental instruction in Portuguese). However, we still found interesting results from the variable importance plots for certain models, which we explore below.

Predicting internet access at home

First, we build random forests for the math and Portuguese data sets.

p <- ncol(d1)
mod.bag.d1 <- randomForest(internet~.,
                         data=d1,

Lets take a look at the variable importance for our model on the math set.

It appears that the mothers job has a large influence over whether or not the household has access to internet, as seen in the Mjob attribute having the highest MeanDecreaseGini. Fjob also has high importance in the model, although definitely not quite as strong. Perhaps this could be explained from certain households having more income available to pay internet bills.

Lets take a look at the model for the Portuguese class.

Again, it appears that the mothers job plays a large role in our model. Here, the course grades also appear to be semi-important predictors. One possible reason for this would be that students with access to internet at home access more written material that interests them (online news, articles, forums, etc.)

In both models, the absences attribute seems to hold relatively high importance as well.

While the MS school has much fewer math students in general, it looks like the MS school has fewer young students for the math data set, which the random forest is picking up on.

Now lets take a look at the Portuguese data sets random forest variables.

For the larger data set for the Portuguese class, address of the student (urban or rural) is a more important factor in determing school. This makes sense, since the MS school is located in a more rural area, while the GP school is more urban, as seen in the plot below.

The variable importance plot suggests that the first grade (G1) is also an important predictor. Comparing the G1 grade across schools, it looks like the GP school has a slightly higher average grade, as seen below.

While the results of these random forests are not helpful for prediction, they give insight into the relationships between the predictors when classifying something other than grade. In addition, these explorations show another way one could extend the analysis of this data set.

Conclusions

During our analysis we found that it was hard to accurately predict final grades when we omitted previous grades regardless of the type of model we were building. When we omitted previous grades, the most telling predictor was the number of previously failed courses. We were able to confirm or reject initial observations from EDA as being important for prediction. Specifically, while we originally thought that urban students tend to outperform rural students, we did not find evidence that address of the student is a significant predictor in their grade. Similarly, we did not find evidence that travel time, study time, and intent to pursue higher education were significant in predicting a students grade. However, we were able to confirm that parents occupations are meaningful in determining student performance. It is fascinating to see how drastically initial observations can change through in-depth analysis.

Instead of finding direct correlations between predictors and grade, we found that grouping the predictors yielded a more interesting and fruitful analysis. While different models gave different sets of variables, the groupings made sense in the context of the data set. Overall, while the models did not give us highly accurate predictions, we saw trends in the variables that were most helpful in predicting grades, such as number of previous failures, parents education, and student age. It is interesting that the different models have different results, which highlights how the choice of model greatly impacts that outcome and analysis, even while working with the same data.
